INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('846', '1', '2013-06-09 06:30:47', '2013-06-09 06:30:47', '<div>\r\n\r\nIt\'s always difficult to report a birth injury case, since it\'s especially heartbreaking to think of newborn infants suffering. Even worse is a case in which the injury could have been prevented. For these reasons, laws exist in Maryland that give victims and their families the right to pursue medical malpractice cases. Not only can this alleviate some of their burden from medical expenses and ongoing treatment and care, but it can give hospital and medical practitioners extra incentive to be sure their procedures are carried out with accuracy and safety, to prevent doctor errors.\r\n\r\nA family was recently awarded $5.25 million in a medical negligence claim against Ohio State University Wexner Medical Center. The Ohio Court of Claims determined the hospital was responsible for the couple\'s son being born with brain damage that resulted in permanent disability in 2006.\r\n\r\nThe baby boy was delivered by an emergency C-section, but the court found that the doctor didn’t properly manage the mother’s labor. He allegedly took too long to realize the C-section was needed, and the baby suffered from blood and oxygen loss. Additionally, two other doctors affirmed that the obstetrician didn’t properly manage the use of Pitocin during the woman’s labor, further resulting in the baby’s permanent brain injury.\r\n\r\nThe boy, now seven years old, requires constant care, which of course has resulted in mounting medical bills. The parents have stated their satisfaction with the settlement, which should help with the compensation of his care and medical expenses. It can also be hoped that more care will be taken with future labors and deliveries to prevent the same type of tragic birth injury from happening to any other babies.\r\n\r\n<b>Source: </b>The Columbus Dispatch, “<a href=\"http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/local/2013/06/27/malpractice-claim-settled.html\" target=\"_blank\">Brain injury during birth costs Ohio State hospital $5.25 million</a>,” Ben Sutherly, June 28, 2013\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Ohio hospital found responsible for birth injury', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'ohio-hospital-found-responsible-for-birth-injury', '', '', '2014-02-28 07:16:40', '2014-02-28 07:16:40', '', '0', 'http://odelugo.laptoppricesinpakistan.com.pk/?p=846', '0', 'post', '', '0');
