INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('868', '1', '2014-02-28 07:16:40', '2014-02-28 07:16:40', '<div>\r\n\r\nIt\'s always difficult to report a birth injury case, since it\'s especially heartbreaking to think of newborn infants suffering. Even worse is a case in which the injury could have been prevented. For these reasons, laws exist in Maryland that give victims and their families the right to pursue medical malpractice cases. Not only can this alleviate some of their burden from medical expenses and ongoing treatment and care, but it can give hospital and medical practitioners extra incentive to be sure their procedures are carried out with accuracy and safety, to prevent doctor errors.\r\n\r\nA family was recently awarded $5.25 million in a medical negligence claim against Ohio State University Wexner Medical Center. The Ohio Court of Claims determined the hospital was responsible for the couple\'s son being born with brain damage that resulted in permanent disability in 2006.\r\n\r\nThe baby boy was delivered by an emergency C-section, but the court found that the doctor didn’t properly manage the mother’s labor. He allegedly took too long to realize the C-section was needed, and the baby suffered from blood and oxygen loss. Additionally, two other doctors affirmed that the obstetrician didn’t properly manage the use of Pitocin during the woman’s labor, further resulting in the baby’s permanent brain injury.\r\n\r\nThe boy, now seven years old, requires constant care, which of course has resulted in mounting medical bills. The parents have stated their satisfaction with the settlement, which should help with the compensation of his care and medical expenses. It can also be hoped that more care will be taken with future labors and deliveries to prevent the same type of tragic birth injury from happening to any other babies.\r\n\r\n<b>Source: </b>The Columbus Dispatch, “<a href=\"http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/local/2013/06/27/malpractice-claim-settled.html\" target=\"_blank\">Brain injury during birth costs Ohio State hospital $5.25 million</a>,” Ben Sutherly, June 28, 2013\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Ohio hospital found responsible for birth injury', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '846-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-02-28 07:16:40', '2014-02-28 07:16:40', '', '846', 'http://odelugo.laptoppricesinpakistan.com.pk/846-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('869', '1', '2013-05-29 07:17:47', '2013-05-29 07:17:47', '<div>\r\n\r\nIt’s a tragedy when the most innocent members of our society, newborn babies, are injured by an error during delivery. Many things can go wrong during labor that can endanger the mother’s or baby’s life, from a doctor making a mistake with equipment to the wrong dosage of medications being administered. It’s possible for a medical malpractice suit to arise from any of these situations, including possible harm that could come from drugs that induce labor.\r\n\r\nA study that was conducted at Beth Israel Medical Center in New York investigated the possibility of the labor-inducing drug Pitocin causing complications during labor or birth injuries. Pitocin is the drug hospitals use most often in the U.S. to start or maintain labor. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention say over 23 percent of pregnant women were induced in 2010.\r\n\r\nThe study followed over 3,000 women who gave birth to full-term babies at Beth Israel between 2009 and 2011. Researchers found a link between the use of Pitocin and a baby’s unexpected stay in the neonatal intensive care unit (NICU) for at least a day. Also, Pitocin may have been a factor in babies’ low Apgar scores--tests of a newborn’s physical condition, of which a score under 7 is cause for concern.\r\n\r\nExperts say that it’s unclear yet whether there are definite risk factors with the drug Pitocin and newborn babies’ health; however, the results of this study may indicate that expectant mothers in Maryland should be aware of the potential risks of the drug.\r\n\r\n<b>Source: </b>Huffington Post, “<a href=\"http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/07/pitocin-risks_n_3224811.html\" target=\"_blank\">Pitocin Risks? Study Raises Concern About Drug’s Safety During Childbirth</a>,” Catherine Pearson, May 7, 2013\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Pitocin study raises birth injury issues', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'pitocin-study-raises-birth-injury-issues', '', '', '2014-02-28 07:19:13', '2014-02-28 07:19:13', '', '0', 'http://odelugo.laptoppricesinpakistan.com.pk/?p=869', '0', 'post', '', '0');
