INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('875', '1', '2013-12-04 07:22:20', '2013-12-04 07:22:20', '<div>\r\n\r\nPeople sustain serious head injuries every day in Maryland and other parts of the country. Whether they are injured in a fall, an automobile collision or other kind of incident, brain injury victims must often contend with lifelong side effects and consequences. And while there is so much that researchers and doctors still don’t know about the nature of many traumatic brain injuries, a new two-year study may help shed light on injury cases and how they relate to other medical conditions.\r\n\r\nThe research study will be conducted by scientists with the Paul G. Allen Institute for Brain Science and the University of Washington, and is expected to cost more than $2 million. Researchers will examine the molecular, structural and cellular makeup of the human brain and analyze how such components are impacted by injury and trauma.\r\n\r\nPaul Allen is spearheading the project, and also asked a neurosurgeon with the University of Washington Seahawks team to collaborate on the research. As the owner of the Seahawks and the cofounder of Microsoft, Allen has the scientific resources and personal investment necessary to propel the study. The NFL is also interested in the project, as it investigates how issues like repeated concussions impact players later in life.\r\n\r\nDonated specimens from Group Health’s brain bank will be used in the study as they represent the largest collection of samples taken from the general public. It’s also estimated that close to 20 percent of the samples sustained some kind of trauma or injury, which allows researchers to investigate how such injuries impacted donors’ health in other ways.\r\n\r\nIt’s reported that the research findings will be accessible to the greater medical community, building hope that this study may further diagnosis and treatment techniques across the globe.\r\n\r\n<b>Source: </b>Seattle Times, “<a href=\"http://seattletimes.com/html/localnews/2022301482_allenbrainstudyxml.html\" target=\"_blank\">Hawks owner Paul Allen funds research into brain injuries</a>,” Sandi Doughton, Nov. 20, 2013\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Major study devoted to brain damage and long-term effects', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'major-study-devoted-to-brain-damage-and-long-term-effects', '', '', '2014-02-28 07:23:14', '2014-02-28 07:23:14', '', '0', 'http://odelugo.laptoppricesinpakistan.com.pk/?p=875', '0', 'post', '', '0');
