INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('877', '1', '2013-11-20 07:23:40', '2013-11-20 07:23:40', '<div>\r\n\r\nWhile thousands of perfectly healthy babies are born every year in Maryland and other states around the country, many others are born with serious medical complications and/or conditions. In many cases, newborn babies require immediate surgery to treat injuries sustained during the birthing process or to address other life-threatening medical issues. Unfortunately, though, many medical procedures can actually compromise patients’ health even further. A new medical device may effectively diagnose brain injury incidents in pediatric heart surgery patients, potentially opening the door to expanded diagnosis and treatment techniques.\r\n\r\nThe biosensor hasn’t been tested on patients yet, but developers are optimistic that the medical device may have a broad range of applications in the future. The end goal may be to use the sensor to identify brain injuries in accident victims. For now, inventors are working to patent their work and promote further research.\r\n\r\nThe new device was actually designed with the intention of diagnosing brain injuries in pediatric heart surgery patients. A pediatric cardiologist with Johns Hopkins Children’s Center first came up with the concept of the biosensor. In America, it’s estimated that a large percentage of children that undergo heart surgery sustain some kind of brain damage. Major medical conditions like strokes can develop during and after surgery, and the results of which often go undiagnosed and untreated in children for years.\r\n\r\nThe appeal of the biosensor is that it may potentially offer an immediate brain injury diagnosis. The sensor is intended to test the patient’s blood for a specific protein linked to brain injuries, alerting physicians to the issue. It’s hoped that the device will be used in operating rooms to better manage pediatric patient care and treatment during and after heart surgeries.\r\n\r\n<b>Source: </b>esciencenews.com, “<a href=\"http://esciencenews.com/articles/2013/11/11/biosensor.could.help.detect.brain.injuries.during.heart.surgery?utm_source=feedburner&amp;utm_medium=feed&amp;utm_campaign=Feed%3A+eScienceNews%2Fpopular+%28e%21+Science+News+-+Popular%29\" target=\"_blank\">Biosensor could help detect brain injuries during heart surgery</a>,” Nov. 11, 2013\r\n\r\n</div>', 'New device may better address some child brain injury cases', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'new-device-may-better-address-some-child-brain-injury-cases', '', '', '2014-02-28 07:24:45', '2014-02-28 07:24:45', '', '0', 'http://odelugo.laptoppricesinpakistan.com.pk/?p=877', '0', 'post', '', '0');
