INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('922', '1', '2014-01-14 09:35:31', '2014-01-14 09:35:31', '<div>\r\n\r\nModern medicine has come so far that many procedures that were once considered major surgeries are now entirely routine. For instance, few dental patients in Hyattsville, Maryland, may blink an eye when they are told they need something like a root canal even though it is considered surgery. No matter how habitual any kind of medical procedure becomes, however, it is the duty of medical professionals to account for possible complications and risks so that they are prepared in the event of an emergency. One dentist is accused of medical malpractice for allegedly failing to prevent and treat complications that resulted in a young patient sustaining severe brain damage.\r\n\r\nThe initial incident occurred in late 2013, when the three-year-old girl in the case underwent a root canal procedure. At that time, the child’s parents claim that she was left unchecked for close to half an hour after being sedated. The dentist that reportedly performed the procedure worked with a children’s dentistry office, and is accused of making serious medication mistakes that caused the child to go into cardiac arrest. It is also argued that the improper dosage and administration of medications during the procedure caused the child to suffer major brain damage.\r\n\r\nThe pediatric patient was later diagnosed as being in a persistent vegetative state as a result of brain damage. At that point she was moved into hospice care from a hospital setting. Sadly, the little girl recently died.\r\n\r\nThe dentistry practice implicated in the case is apparently closed down; though, the dentist identified as the defendant in the malpractice lawsuit had no comment. The parents of the young victim are accusing the dentist and facility of recklessness and negligence. Their lawsuit claims that the defendant was ill-equipped to handle the medical emergency their daughter experienced.\r\n\r\n<b>Source: </b>CNN, “<a href=\"http://www.cnn.com/2014/01/04/justice/hawaii-girl-dead/index.html\" target=\"_blank\">Hawaii girl, 3, dies after dental procedure</a>,” Khushbu Shah, Jan. 4, 2014\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Pediatric patient may have been victim of anesthesia error', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'pediatric-patient-may-have-been-victim-of-anesthesia-error', '', '', '2014-02-28 09:36:29', '2014-02-28 09:36:29', '', '0', 'http://odelugo.laptoppricesinpakistan.com.pk/?p=922', '0', 'post', '', '0');
