INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('926', '1', '2013-12-19 09:38:26', '2013-12-19 09:38:26', '<div>\r\n\r\nThese days, most people may agree that something like a minor cold can be a major setback when it comes to working and taking care of a family. And even when an individual has medical insurance in Maryland, they still may not be able to afford to experience any kind of ailment and/or medical complication. One woman’s life will forever be impacted by a seemingly straightforward medical procedure she underwent years ago. Now, she’s attempting to hold her doctors responsible for allegedly causing her permanent disability in a major medical malpractice lawsuit.\r\n\r\nThe plaintiff in the medical malpractice lawsuit underwent laparoscopic surgery to remove an ectopic pregnancy in October of 2009. The woman and mother of a teenage daughter claims that she was discharged from the hospital only days after the procedure even though she was still in extreme pain. She was ultimately readmitted to the hospital for emergency surgery and care.\r\n\r\nAfter waking up in the hospital weeks later, the woman claims that she learned she had suffered from sepsis and gangrene, which resulted in both her legs being amputated from the knee down. The plaintiff also sustained scarring to other parts of her body and now suffers from hearing loss caused by the aggressive antibiotic treatment required to treat her infection.\r\n\r\nDuring the course of the malpractice trial an expert testified that the medical complications leading to the woman’s medical crisis could have been avoided. Surgeons allegedly punctured the woman’s colon during her initial surgery.\r\n\r\nThe hospital argues that doctors responded appropriately to the woman’s medical condition and saved her life. However, she contends that her mobility and way of life have been seriously affected by her double amputation.\r\n\r\n<b>Source: </b>New York Daily News, “<a href=\"http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/brooklyn/eclusive-hospital-victim-procedure-worse-article-1.1537002\" target=\"_blank\">EXCLUSIVE: Hospital victim says procedure led to legs being amputated: ‘It was a sharp, driving pain. And it kept getting wors</a>e,’” Oren Yaniv, Dec. 4, 201\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Double amputation may have been caused by surgical error', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'double-amputation-may-have-been-caused-by-surgical-error', '', '', '2014-02-28 09:39:51', '2014-02-28 09:39:51', '', '0', 'http://odelugo.laptoppricesinpakistan.com.pk/?p=926', '0', 'post', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('927', '1', '2014-02-28 09:39:51', '2014-02-28 09:39:51', '<div>\r\n\r\nThese days, most people may agree that something like a minor cold can be a major setback when it comes to working and taking care of a family. And even when an individual has medical insurance in Maryland, they still may not be able to afford to experience any kind of ailment and/or medical complication. One woman’s life will forever be impacted by a seemingly straightforward medical procedure she underwent years ago. Now, she’s attempting to hold her doctors responsible for allegedly causing her permanent disability in a major medical malpractice lawsuit.\r\n\r\nThe plaintiff in the medical malpractice lawsuit underwent laparoscopic surgery to remove an ectopic pregnancy in October of 2009. The woman and mother of a teenage daughter claims that she was discharged from the hospital only days after the procedure even though she was still in extreme pain. She was ultimately readmitted to the hospital for emergency surgery and care.\r\n\r\nAfter waking up in the hospital weeks later, the woman claims that she learned she had suffered from sepsis and gangrene, which resulted in both her legs being amputated from the knee down. The plaintiff also sustained scarring to other parts of her body and now suffers from hearing loss caused by the aggressive antibiotic treatment required to treat her infection.\r\n\r\nDuring the course of the malpractice trial an expert testified that the medical complications leading to the woman’s medical crisis could have been avoided. Surgeons allegedly punctured the woman’s colon during her initial surgery.\r\n\r\nThe hospital argues that doctors responded appropriately to the woman’s medical condition and saved her life. However, she contends that her mobility and way of life have been seriously affected by her double amputation.\r\n\r\n<b>Source: </b>New York Daily News, “<a href=\"http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/brooklyn/eclusive-hospital-victim-procedure-worse-article-1.1537002\" target=\"_blank\">EXCLUSIVE: Hospital victim says procedure led to legs being amputated: ‘It was a sharp, driving pain. And it kept getting wors</a>e,’” Oren Yaniv, Dec. 4, 201\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Double amputation may have been caused by surgical error', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '926-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-02-28 09:39:51', '2014-02-28 09:39:51', '', '926', 'http://odelugo.laptoppricesinpakistan.com.pk/926-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('928', '1', '2013-12-28 09:42:46', '2013-12-28 09:42:46', '<div>\r\n\r\nThe truth of the matter is that thousands of babies are born with life-threatening conditions every year in Maryland, and many continue to face difficulties their entire lives. And while countless families approach such obstacles with grace and compassion, sometimes they are left to live with the consequences of others’ avoidable mistakes. A jury recently ruled in favor of a family that filed a medical malpractice lawsuit against several medical staff for causing their son to endure potentially fatal birth injuries.\r\n\r\nThe child at the heart of the case is now nine years old. At the time of his premature birth, the child experienced a life-threatening medical condition associated with his early arrival. The boy’s parents claim that the nurse practitioner and two doctors attending to their son did not respond to his medical crisis in the correct manner, which ultimately resulted in his current medical state. After having a section of his intestines removed, the young boy must rely on a feeding tube for nutrition.\r\n\r\nFor its part, the hospital where the child was born claims that the boy’s condition is unfortunate. However, the hospital contends that his care and medical needs were handled correctly throughout the entire incident. In its argument, the hospital added that the boy’s medical condition takes the lives of many children every year.\r\n\r\nThe family of the boy apparently agreed to a maximum and minimum award figure with the defendants in the lawsuit before any verdict was issued. As a result, they may receive the maximum judgment of $5.3 million even though the jury awarded them $30 million. They may now pursue other means of achieving the full amount.\r\n\r\n<b>Source: </b>boston.com, “<a href=\"http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/2013/11/21/lowell-family-receive-least-malpractice-suit-against-tufts-medical-center/LE6KSbzmwkLnJAgrTeqrVI/story.html\" target=\"_blank\">Lowell family to receive at least $5m in malpractice suit against Tufts Medical Center</a>,” Travis Anderson, Nov. 21, 2013\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Nine years later, family wins birth injury lawsuit', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'nine-years-later-family-wins-birth-injury-lawsuit', '', '', '2014-02-28 09:43:39', '2014-02-28 09:43:39', '', '0', 'http://odelugo.laptoppricesinpakistan.com.pk/?p=928', '0', 'post', '', '0');
