INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('938', '1', '2013-10-18 09:50:52', '2013-10-18 09:50:52', '<div>\r\n\r\nToo often in the medical community, avoidable and potentially life-threatening medical mistakes go unchecked and unpunished. Maryland hospital patients can be incredibly vulnerable to medical malpractice and negligence. Provided below are a few helpful points every hospital patient should keep in mind to help safeguard their own health and security.\r\n\r\n<strong>Be your own advocate</strong>\r\n\r\nWhen someone is admitted to the hospital, personal information like his or her medical chart becomes available to providers. As a result, hospital personnel like physicians, pharmacy techs and insurance reps have access to sensitive information. Following any hospital visit, it’s recommended that patients monitor details like their credit scores.\r\n\r\nHospital patients are also allowed to specify who may have access to their case and why. If the patient is not comfortable with interns and/or med students being on their care team, he or she has the right to say so.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, patients have the right to protect themselves against the risk of infection by insisting that all care providers comply with proper hygiene standards. Ensuring that hospital staff washes their hands before any consultation helps to prevent the spread of infection.\r\n\r\nPatients can also be subject to injury and illness because of issues like nursing shortages and long ER wait times. Both are known to contribute to the patient fatality rates. Avoiding hospitals with problems like nursing shortages can help to improve the quality of care provided. It’s also important for patients to take into account that staffing issues can cause delays in bedside response times and care.\r\n\r\nLast but not least, every patient should confirm that the medication they receive is the correct drug and dosage every time. By being proactive in their care, hospital patients can help ensure their own safety and well-being.\r\n\r\n<b>Source: </b>Yahoo! Health, “<a href=\"http://health.yahoo.net/articles/healthcare/photos/protect-yourself-8-common-mistakes-made-hospital-staffs#0\" target=\"_blank\">Protect Yourself: Eight Common Mistakes Made by Hospital Staffs</a>,” Cindy Kuzma, Oct. 7, 2013\r\n\r\n</div>', 'Protecting Maryland patients against medical malpractice', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'protecting-maryland-patients-against-medical-malpractice', '', '', '2014-02-28 09:51:54', '2014-02-28 09:51:54', '', '0', 'http://odelugo.laptoppricesinpakistan.com.pk/?p=938', '0', 'post', '', '0');
INSERT INTO spk_posts VALUES('939', '1', '2014-02-28 09:51:54', '2014-02-28 09:51:54', '<div>\r\n\r\nToo often in the medical community, avoidable and potentially life-threatening medical mistakes go unchecked and unpunished. Maryland hospital patients can be incredibly vulnerable to medical malpractice and negligence. Provided below are a few helpful points every hospital patient should keep in mind to help safeguard their own health and security.\r\n\r\n<strong>Be your own advocate</strong>\r\n\r\nWhen someone is admitted to the hospital, personal information like his or her medical chart becomes available to providers. As a result, hospital personnel like physicians, pharmacy techs and insurance reps have access to sensitive information. Following any hospital visit, it’s recommended that patients monitor details like their credit scores.\r\n\r\nHospital patients are also allowed to specify who may have access to their case and why. If the patient is not comfortable with interns and/or med students being on their care team, he or she has the right to say so.\r\n\r\nFurthermore, patients have the right to protect themselves against the risk of infection by insisting that all care providers comply with proper hygiene standards. Ensuring that hospital staff washes their hands before any consultation helps to prevent the spread of infection.\r\n\r\nPatients can also be subject to injury and illness because of issues like nursing shortages and long ER wait times. Both are known to contribute to the patient fatality rates. Avoiding hospitals with problems like nursing shortages can help to improve the quality of care provided. It’s also important for patients to take into account that staffing issues can cause delays in bedside response times and care.\r\n\r\nLast but not least, every patient should confirm that the medication they receive is the correct drug and dosage every time. By being proactive in their care, hospital patients can help ensure their own safety and